Applied to those who have held office at the DES since 1976, such observations only partially fit the facts. Thus while five did go to public schools and Oxbridge (Hancock, Caines, Holland, Lankester, Normington), three attended state schools and Red Brick universities (Hamilton, Bichard, Bell
10
). Regarding those he studied, Sherratt (2004: 2) suggests that they, or indeed other senior DES civil servants, have ‘seldom, if ever, been accused of boasting right-wing credentials’. Rather, ‘if there is a tendency among (them) to an innate conservatism then this has little to do with party preferences and everything to do with the fact that senior officials tend to resist too much change, preferring to maintain policy continuity, stability and sustainability despite reshuffles and changes in government’ (Sherratt, 2004: 2).
